To reset the timer when `ActivateAndDisableAfterTime` is called again, we need a little modification to ensure that any previous delayed calls to `DisableGameObject` are cancelled before scheduling a new one. This will prevent multiple overlapping disable calls from occurring.

Here's how to modify the script:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class UIDisableAfterTime : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float disableAfterSeconds = 2f; // Time in seconds until the UI is disabled
    private bool isActive = false;

    public void ActivateAndDisableAfterTime()
    {
        if (isActive)
        {
            // Cancel the previous disable call if the GameObject is already active
            CancelInvoke("DisableGameObject");
        }
        else
        {
            // Activate the GameObject if it's not active
            gameObject.SetActive(true);
            isActive = true;
        }

        // Invoke the disable method after a delay - this will override any previous calls
        Invoke("DisableGameObject", disableAfterSeconds);
    }

    private void DisableGameObject()
    {
        gameObject.SetActive(false);
        isActive = false;
    }
}

```

In this script, we track whether the GameObject is currently active with the `isActive` flag. When `ActivateAndDisableAfterTime` is called:

- If the GameObject is already active (which means a disable call is scheduled), we use `CancelInvoke` to cancel the pending invocation of `DisableGameObject`.
- If the GameObject is not active, we activate it and set `isActive` to `true`.
- Then we use `Invoke` to schedule `DisableGameObject` after the specified delay.

With these changes, calling `ActivateAndDisableAfterTime` will reset the timer each time, safely ensuring there's only one scheduled disable operation. If the method is called before the timer expires, it will extend the active period by `disableAfterSeconds` from the time of the call.

To lerp (linearly interpolate) from one light color to another, you can use the `Color.Lerp` function provided by Unity. You will lerp between two colors over time, often within the `Update` method or a coroutine for smooth transitions.

Below is an example script that lerps the color of a Light component between two specified colors:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;

public class LightColorLerp : MonoBehaviour
{
    public Light targetLight;          // Reference to the Light component
    public Color startColor;           // The initial color of the light
    public Color endColor;             // The final color to lerp to
    public float lerpDuration = 2f;    // Duration over which the color lerping occurs

    private float lerpProgress;        // Tracks the progress of the lerp

    void Start()
    {
        // Initialize the light color and lerp progress
        if (targetLight != null)
        {
            targetLight.color = startColor;
        }
        lerpProgress = 0f;
    }

    void Update()
    {
        if (lerpProgress < 1f) // Check if we haven't finished lerping
        {
            lerpProgress += Time.deltaTime / lerpDuration; // Increment lerp progress based on time

            if (targetLight != null)
            {
                // Perform the lerp from startColor to endColor based on the current lerp progress
                targetLight.color = Color.Lerp(startColor, endColor, lerpProgress);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Attach this script to any GameObject (it doesn't have to be a Light GameObject). Then, in the Unity Editor, drag and drop the Light component you want to affect into the `targetLight` field. Additionally, specify the `startColor`, `endColor`, and `lerpDuration`.

- `startColor` is the color the light will start with.
- `endColor` is the color the light will change to over the specified duration.
- `lerpDuration` determines how long the entire color transition will take.

The `Update` method updates the `lerpProgress` based on time, and `Color.Lerp` is used to calculate the intermediate color value each frame. When `lerpProgress` reaches 1, the color transition is complete, and updating stops.

